# Coding standards

## TypeScript

- Strict mode is on. No `any`. No type assertions (`as Foo`) without a comment explaining why.
- Use `type` for unions, primitives, and function signatures. Use `interface` for objects that may be extended.
- All database row types come from `@/lib/supabase/types.ts` (generated). Never hand-write DB types.
- Zod for all external input validation: form submissions, API route bodies, URL params, webhook payloads.

```ts
// Good
const paramsSchema = z.object({
  kategori: z.string().min(1),
  subkategori: z.string().min(1),
  by: z.string().optional(),
})

// Bad — trusting params directly
const { kategori, subkategori } = params
```

## Naming conventions

| Thing | Convention | Example |
|---|---|---|
| Components | PascalCase | `ProviderCard.tsx` |
| Hooks | camelCase with `use` prefix | `useProviderList.ts` |
| Lib functions | camelCase | `calculateFees()` |
| DB column names | snake_case | `base_price_ore` |
| URL slugs | kebab-case, ASCII | `bryllupsfotografi`, `oslo` |
| Translation keys | dot-notation, snake_case | `provider.badge.verified` |
| Env vars | SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE | `STRIPE_SECRET_KEY` |
| Constants | SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE | `BUYER_FEE_RATE` |

## Component patterns

### Prefer Server Components
Default to Server Components. Only add `'use client'` when you need:
- `useState` / `useEffect`
- Browser APIs (geolocation, localStorage)
- Event handlers on interactive elements
- Third-party client libs (Mapbox, Stripe Elements)

### Component file structure
```tsx
// 1. Imports — external, then internal, then types
import { type FC } from 'react'
import { MapPin } from 'lucide-react'
import { cn } from '@/lib/utils'
import type { ProviderWithServices } from '@/types/database'

// 2. Types for this component only
type Props = {
  provider: ProviderWithServices
  className?: string
}

// 3. Component — named export, no default export for components
export function ProviderCard({ provider, className }: Props) {
  return (
    <div className={cn('...', className)}>
      {/* ... */}
    </div>
  )
}
```

No default exports for components. Default exports only for Next.js `page.tsx` and `layout.tsx`.

### Props
- `className` prop on every reusable component for composability
- Use `cn()` (clsx + tailwind-merge) to merge classes
- Never pass raw style objects — use Tailwind only

## Tailwind usage

This project uses the Hjelpi design system. Always use the custom tokens defined in `tailwind.config.ts`, not raw hex values.

### Color tokens
```
bg-primary           #00606c  (deep teal — CTAs, active states)
bg-secondary         #29657a  (soft azure)
bg-surface           #f8f9ff  (page background)
bg-surface-container-low      #eff4ff  (section backgrounds)
bg-surface-container-lowest   #ffffff  (cards)
text-on-surface      #0b1c30
text-on-surface-variant  #3e494b
text-tertiary        #745100  (gold accent — ratings, badges)
bg-secondary-container  #ace5fe  (chip unselected state)
border-outline-variant  #bdc8cb
```

### Typography tokens
```
font-headline        Manrope   (headings h1–h4)
font-body            Inter     (body text, labels)
```

### The no-border rule
Never use `border border-gray-200` or similar for section separation. Use background color shifts instead:
```tsx
// Bad
<div className="border border-gray-200 rounded-xl p-4">

// Good — card lifts from surface-container-low background
<div className="bg-surface-container-lowest rounded-3xl p-8 shadow-[0px_10px_30px_rgba(11,28,48,0.03)]">
```

### Shadow token
Always use the tonal shadow: `shadow-[0px_10px_30px_rgba(11,28,48,0.05)]`
Never use `shadow-md`, `shadow-lg`, or any pure-black shadow.

### Glassmorphism (nav and floating bars only)
```tsx
<nav className="bg-white/70 backdrop-blur-md shadow-[0px_10px_30px_rgba(11,28,48,0.05)]">
```

## Import order (enforced by ESLint)
1. React
2. Next.js (`next/...`)
3. External packages (alphabetical)
4. Internal aliases (`@/lib/...`, `@/components/...`, `@/types/...`)
5. Relative imports (`./`, `../`)
6. Type-only imports last

## Error handling

Use `Result` pattern for lib functions that can fail:
```ts
type Result<T> = { data: T; error: null } | { data: null; error: string }
```

In Server Components and API routes, catch Supabase and Stripe errors explicitly — never let them bubble as unhandled exceptions.

```ts
const { data, error } = await supabase.from('providers').select('*')
if (error) {
  // log to Sentry, return appropriate UI
  return <ErrorState message="Kunne ikke laste leverandører" />
}
```

## Internationalisation

All user-facing strings go through `next-intl`. No hardcoded Norwegian strings in components.

```tsx
import { useTranslations } from 'next-intl'

export function SearchBar() {
  const t = useTranslations('search')
  return <input placeholder={t('placeholder')} />
}
```

Translation keys live in `messages/no.json`. Add the key there before using it.

## Breadcrumbs

Every category, subcategory, and provider page must render:
1. A visible `<Breadcrumbs>` component using the `layout/Breadcrumbs` component
2. A `BreadcrumbList` JSON-LD script in the page `<head>` via Next.js Metadata API

```ts
// Every subcategory page exports this
export function generateBreadcrumbJsonLd(params) {
  return {
    '@context': 'https://schema.org',
    '@type': 'BreadcrumbList',
    itemListElement: [
      { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 1, name: 'Hjem', item: 'https://hjelpi.com/no' },
      { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 2, name: kategoriName, item: `https://hjelpi.com/no/${params.kategori}` },
      { '@type': 'ListItem', position: 3, name: subkategoriName, item: `https://hjelpi.com/no/${params.kategori}/${params.subkategori}` },
    ],
  }
}
```

## Formatting

- Prettier with default settings
- 2-space indent
- Single quotes
- No semicolons (configured in prettier)
- Trailing commas in multi-line structures
